We have talked before about the problems of meme-stock corporate governance=
, and particularly=C2=A0the problem of meme-stock shareholder voting. The p=
roblem is:
=09If you=E2=80=99re a weird public company with a very retail investor bas=
e, you will have a hard time getting your shareholders to vote=C2=A0on anyt=
hing, since retail shareholders stereotypically do not vote.=09If you=E2=80=
=99re a weird public company with a very retail investor base, you will pro=
bably end up=C2=A0needing=C2=A0your shareholders to vote for something or o=
ther, because you=E2=80=99re weird.

So Digital World Acquisition Corp. wanted to get shareholder approval to ex=
tend the time on its deal to buy Donald Trump=E2=80=99s social media compan=
y, but   it couldn=E2=80=99t get it, because the retail shareholders who we=
re extremely enthusiastic about buying its stock, and about the deal, were =
not enthusiastic enough to vote. Or AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc. has a l=
ot of enthusiastic retail shareholders, and it got very good at=C2=A0sellin=
g them stock, but it eventually ran out of authorized shares to sell, and i=
t needed holders of a majority of its outstanding shares to vote to authori=
ze more, and it couldn=E2=80=99t get enough votes.
AMC   (probably) solved this problem with some clever engineering. It creat=
ed a new class of preferred stock, gave each preferred share 100 votes, and=
 distributed 1/100th of a preferred share for each common share, basically =
a stock split where if you had one common share with one vote now you had o=
ne common share and 1/100th of a preferred share with a total of two votes.=
 (The 1/100th of a preferred share is called an APE, an AMC Preferred Equit=
y Unit.) It=E2=80=99s not obvious that this would change much =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0you still have to get a majority of the combined APE and common holders =
to vote to authorize more shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0but AMC added a clever twis=
t. It issued the preferred shares to a depositary, Computershare Trust Co.,=
 and had Computershare issue the APE units to AMC=E2=80=99s shareholders. S=
o now 100% of the preferred shares are owned, not by a bunch of retail shar=
eholders, but by Computershare. The retail APE holders still get to vote, a=
nd Computershare still has to vote=C2=A0its=C2=A0shares however the APE hol=
ders vote, but Computershare has to vote=C2=A0all=C2=A0of the shares: If 20=
% of the APE holders vote yes, 5% vote no, and 75% don=E2=80=99t vote at al=
l, then Computershare will vote 80% of the preferred shares for yes and 20%=
 for no. AMC still needs to=C2=A0win the vote, but it has solved the proble=
m of=C2=A0retail shareholders not voting at all.
  [3]

Soligenix Inc. is a micro-cap biotech company listed on the Nasdaq. Nasdaq =
will delist companies whose stocks trade below $1 per share for an extended=
 period. Soligenix=E2=80=99s stock traded below $1 for a long time, and Nas=
daq threatened=C2=A0it with delisting starting in December 2021. By Decembe=
r 2022 it was still below $1 and  in real danger of delisting. The normal s=
olution here is a reverse stock split: If your stock trades at $0.70, and y=
ou do a 1-for-10 reverse stock split, then every 10 shares (each worth $0.7=
0) become one share, which should be worth $7.00. But you need shareholder =
approval for the split, and Soligenix was worried about its ability to get =
a majority of its retail, penny-stock shareholders to vote for anything.
  [4]

So Soligenix came up with an APE-like solution. Like AMC, it  issued new =
=E2=80=9Cblank-check preferred stock=E2=80=9D; each share of its new Series=
 D preferred stock came with=C2=A0one million=C2=A0votes.
  [5]
=C2=A0And it distributed the preferred shares to its common shareholders, g=
iving them each 1/1,000th of a preferred share (with 1,000 votes) for each =
common share that they own. So effectively all of the voting power of the c=
ompany is in the Series D preferred, but the voting rights don=E2=80=99t re=
ally change, because every existing common shareholder owns the same propor=
tional amount of Series D preferred.
But the Series D preferred stock is a temporary blip: Soligenix issued it i=
n December, and it all disappeared last week.
  [6]
=C2=A0It never traded, had no cash value, was issued to shareholders for $0=
 and then redeemed by the company for $0.
  [7]
 For a couple of months Soligenix had some extra shares with billions of vo=
tes, and now it doesn=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0
Why? Well, here are the mechanics of how the Series D disappeared:
All shares of Series D Preferred Stock that are not present in person or by=
 proxy at the meeting of stockholders held to vote on the reverse stock spl=
it as of immediately prior to the opening of the polls at such meeting will=
 automatically be redeemed by the Company. Any outstanding shares of Series=
 D Preferred Stock that have not been so redeemed will be redeemed if such =
redemption is ordered by the Company=E2=80=99s Board of Directors or automa=
tically upon the approval by the Company=E2=80=99s stockholders of an amend=
ment to the Company=E2=80=99s certificate of incorporation effecting the re=
verse stock split at such meeting.
Get it? Soligenix  held a shareholder meeting last Wednesday, Feb. 8. If yo=
u voted at the shareholder meeting =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is, if you filled ou=
t your proxy to vote your shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0then your preferred stock g=
ot canceled immediately=C2=A0after=C2=A0the vote. If you didn=E2=80=99t vot=
e =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you forgot or were unreachable or whatever =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0then your preferred stock got canceled immediately=C2=A0before=C2=A0the =
vote. At the moment of the vote, the preferred stock represented roughly 99=
.9% of the voting power of the company, and only the preferred shares that=
=C2=A0actually voted=C2=A0were outstanding. They voted overwhelmingly for t=
he reverse split, and it passed.
  [8]
 Soligenix  did a 1-for-15 reverse stock split, and the Series D disappeare=
d back into the lawyer=E2=80=99s imagination from whence it came.
Is this legal? I mean, the answer is:
=09nothing here is ever legal advice;=09it is=C2=A0funny, anyway, and isn=
=E2=80=99t that the=C2=A0real=C2=A0purpose of securities lawyering; and=09w=
ho would=C2=A0object?

The large majority of the shareholders who bothered to vote wanted this res=
ult; Soligenix just found a way to give it to them.=C2=A0

