10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Crypto custody</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Roughly speaking the way the US stock=C2=A0mar=
ket works is that all of the stocks are in one place. The place is called D=
TC, the Depository Trust Company, which in some sense owns almost all of th=
e stocks. If you own a stock, what you own is an entry on a list at your br=
okerage, saying that you are entitled to some of the stocks that it is hold=
ing onto for clients, and what your=C2=A0brokerage=C2=A0has is an entry on =
a list at DTC, saying that it is entitled to some of the stocks that DTC is=
 holding onto. (And what DTC mostly owns is entries on lists at all the com=
panies, or their transfer agents, saying that it owns the stocks that those=
 companies issue.)=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One thing this means is that when I buy some s=
tock from you, the way we settle that transaction =E2=80=94=C2=A0the way yo=
u actually deliver the stock to me =E2=80=94=C2=A0is by updating DTC=E2=80=
=99s list. We tell DTC about the transaction, it increments the stock in my=
 account (really my broker=E2=80=99s, who increments my account) and decrem=
ents the stock in yours. This is far more efficient than if, for instance, =
you owned your stock in the form of paper stock certificates, and to settle=
 trades you had to courier those certificates over to me, which is pretty m=
uch how things worked in the olden days.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another thing this means is that DTC is an ext=
remely important weird market utility, highly trusted and so heavily regula=
ted. =E2=80=9CDTC is a member of the U.S. Federal Reserve System, a limited=
-purpose trust company under New York State banking law and a registered cl=
earing agency with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission,=E2=80=9D <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30575723.282980/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuZHRjYy5jb20vYWJvdXQvYnVzaW5lc3Nlcy1hbmQtc3Vic2lkaWFyaWVzL2R0Yw/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8fb9d61d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> says its website</a>, on the sa=
me page that also mentions that it holds $87 trillion worth of securities.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way the crypto market works is a bit diffe=
rent. One way for crypto to work is that there is a blockchain, a decentral=
ized ledger maintained by thousands of independent nodes, and you can own s=
ome Bitcoin on the blockchain, and you and I can agree on a trade in which =
I send you some dollars (by wire transfer or Venmo or whatever) and you sen=
d me some Bitcoin on the Bitcoin blockchain. How do we meet each other and =
agree to that trade? You could imagine some sort of exchange =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0like US stock exchanges =E2=80=94=C2=A0that allows us to post orders to =
buy and sell crypto, and if our orders cross =E2=80=94=C2=A0if I want to bu=
y and you want to sell =E2=80=94=C2=A0then we are matched with each other a=
nd then settle up using Venmo and the blockchain. This can work in some sor=
t of informal way (like, a message board for us to meet and negotiate trade=
s), or in modern crypto you can have decentralized exchanges built on smart=
 contracts where trades and settlements all occur on the blockchain.<a clas=
s=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent =
!important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But practically speaking the way that a=C2=A0<=
em>lot=C2=A0</em>of crypto works is more like the stock market: There is so=
me central intermediary, much like DTC, that holds onto a lot of crypto for=
 a lot of investors; we can call it the =E2=80=9Cdepository.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=
The investors agree on a trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0you agree to sell me some Bit=
coin =E2=80=94=C2=A0on an exchange, and then we settle that trade by updati=
ng our accounts with the depository. There are some differences, though:</p=
>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The depository is normally=C2=A0<em>a=
lso the exchange:=C2=A0</em>If you and I are trading on Coinbase, Coinbase =
is holding onto our crypto for us and updating its ledger when we agree to =
a trade on its exchange. This is different from the stock market, where the=
 exchanges =E2=80=94=C2=A0NYSE and Nasdaq and so forth =E2=80=94=C2=A0are s=
eparate from DTC.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There is normall=
y=C2=A0<em>one depository per exchange: </em>If you have some Bitcoin on Bi=
nance, and you and I agree on a trade on Coinbase, you can=E2=80=99t just i=
nstantly send me your Binance Bitcoins to settle that trade. Each exchange =
has its own depository, unlike in the US stock market, where you and I can =
agree a trade on NYSE or Nasdaq or wherever and then settle up using DTC.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The exchange is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I me=
an =E2=80=A6=C2=A0less trusted by US regulatory authorities than DTC is? To=
 be clear, DTC is very trusted by US regulatory authorities; it is a center=
piece of modern securities markets. Crypto exchanges range from, you know, =
=E2=80=9Cnot=C2=A0<em>quite=C2=A0</em>as trusted as DTC=E2=80=9D to, uh, we=
ll, much worse than that.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the US, the Securities and Exchange Commiss=
ion regulates =E2=80=9Cinvestment advisers,=E2=80=9D which means not only p=
eople who advise clients about their investments, but also people and firms=
 who manage=C2=A0<em>funds</em>; <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90=
ZXh0LzE3LzI3NS4yMDMobSktMQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB943e52b6" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">big</=
a> hedge funds and mutual funds are generally managed by registered investm=
ent advisers. There <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI3N=
S4yMDYoNCktMg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd6e55548" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> are rules</a> abo=
ut an investment adviser=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>custody=C2=A0</em>of client ass=
ets: You can=E2=80=99t just keep your client=E2=80=99s stock certificates i=
n a pile under your desk; those assets need to be held by a =E2=80=9Cqualif=
ied custodian=E2=80=9D in your client=E2=80=99s name. And there are standar=
d ways to implement this; there are trust companies and brokerages that are=
 in the business of being custodians for investment advisers, and that effe=
ctively own the advisers=E2=80=99 clients=E2=80=99 stocks through DTC.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Historically those rules have applied to =E2=
=80=9Cclient funds or securities=E2=80=9D: The SEC regulates securities tra=
des, and so it focuses mostly on securities and money. But in the Dodd-Fran=
k Act of 2010, Congress gave the SEC power to regulate advisers=E2=80=99 cu=
stody of client =E2=80=9Cassets,=E2=80=9D which seems to include not just s=
ecurities and money but also real estate, derivatives, etc.<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And =E2=80=94=C2=A0though probably nobody thou=
ght much=C2=A0about it at the time =E2=80=94=C2=A0crypto. And so yesterday =
the SEC <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30575723.2=
82980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy0zMA/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBda39fee6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> proposed new rules</a> for custody of=
 client assets:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The proposed rules would exercise =
Commission authority under section 411 of the Dodd-Frank Act by broadening =
the application of the current investment adviser custody rule beyond clien=
t funds and securities to include any client assets in an investment advise=
r=E2=80=99s possession or when an investment adviser has authority to obtai=
n possession of client assets. Like the current rule, the proposed rule wou=
ld entrust safekeeping of client assets to qualified custodians, including,=
 for example, certain banks or broker-dealers.<br /><br />The proposed chan=
ges are intended to help ensure that qualified custodians provide certain s=
tandard custodial protections when maintaining an advisory client=E2=80=99s=
 assets. These protections are designed, among other things, to ensure clie=
nt assets are properly segregated and held in accounts to protect the asset=
s in the event of a qualified custodian bankruptcy or other insolvency.</p>=
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose that this is about lots of things, i=
ncluding the mechanics of the adviser/custodian relationship, surprise exam=
inations of client assets, etc., but it is especially about crypto. SEC Cha=
ir Gary=C2=A0Gensler <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3N0YXRlbWVudC9nZW5zbGVy=
LXN0YXRlbWVudC1jdXN0b2R5LTAyMTUyMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB50eda6b9" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> said in a statement</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Make no mistake: Today=E2=80=99s rule, the 200=
9 rule, covers a significant amount of crypto assets. As the release states=
, =E2=80=9Cmost crypto assets are likely to be funds or crypto asset securi=
ties covered by the current rule.=E2=80=9D Further, though some crypto trad=
ing and lending platforms may claim to custody investors=E2=80=99 crypto, t=
hat does not mean they are qualified custodians. Rather than properly segre=
gating investors=E2=80=99 crypto, these platforms have commingled those ass=
ets with their own crypto or other investors=E2=80=99 crypto. When these pl=
atforms go bankrupt=E2=80=94something we=E2=80=99ve seen time and again rec=
ently=E2=80=94investors=E2=80=99 assets often have become property of the f=
ailed company, leaving investors in line at the bankruptcy court.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Make no mistake: Based upon how crypto platfor=
ms generally operate, investment advisers cannot rely on them as qualified =
custodians.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Further, today=E2=80=99s proposal, in covering=
 all asset classes, would cover all crypto assets=E2=80=94including those t=
hat currently are covered as funds and securities and those that are not fu=
nds or securities. Thus, through this expanded custody rule, investors work=
ing with advisers would receive the time-tested protections that they deser=
ve for all of their assets, including crypto assets, consistent with what C=
ongress envisioned.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A couple of points here. First, the effect of =
this rule is to ban registered advisers from=C2=A0<em>trading=C2=A0</em>cry=
pto on=C2=A0<em>most=C2=A0</em>exchanges: To trade crypto on most centraliz=
ed exchanges, you need to deposit the crypto on the exchange first, which d=
estroys custody. From the proposed rule:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Importantly, however, to comply wi=
th the proposed rule, an adviser with custody of client=C2=A0crypto assets =
would generally need to ensure those assets are maintained with a qualified=
 custodian that has possession or control of the assets at all times in whi=
ch the adviser has custody. While this is true for most client assets over =
which an adviser has custody, it is particularly relevant with respect to c=
rypto assets because, as we understand, much of the crypto asset trading vo=
lume occurs on crypto asset trading platforms that often directly settle th=
e trades placed on their platforms. As a result, many crypto trading platfo=
rms require investors to pre-fund trades, a process in which investors tran=
sfer their crypto assets, including crypto asset securities, or fiat curren=
cy to such an exchange prior to the execution of any trade. Because we unde=
rstand that most crypto assets, including crypto asset securities, trade on=
 platforms that are not qualified custodians, this practice would generally=
 result in an adviser with custody of a crypto asset security being in viol=
ation of the current custody rule because custody of the crypto asset secur=
ity would not be maintained by a qualified custodian from the time the cryp=
to asset security was moved to the trading platform through the settlement =
of the trade.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can trade stocks on the stock exchange bec=
ause the stocks live at DTC and you own them through a qualified custodian,=
 but if you trade crypto on Binance then the crypto lives at Binance and th=
e SEC might have concerns. Some crypto exchanges have custody services that=
 probably qualify =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9CPaul Grewal, <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLm=
NvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9zZWMtY29uc2lkZXJzLXJ1bGVzLXRoYXQtY291bGQtdGhyZWF0ZW4tY3J5c=
HRvLWN1c3RvZHktc2VydmljZXMtODliYTRjZDU_bW9kPWl0cF93c2omcnU9eWFob28/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB799bd90e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Coinbase=E2=80=99s chief legal officer<=
/a>, said the firm is confident that its New York-chartered trust entity =
=E2=80=98will remain a qualified custodian=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 but =
your choices are more limited. SEC Commissioner Mark Uyeda <a href=3D"https=
://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2=
VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3N0YXRlbWVudC91eWVkYS1zdGF0ZW1lbnQtY3VzdG9keS0wMjE1MjM/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB0329d706" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> said in his statement</a>=C2=A0that =
=E2=80=9Cthe proposing release takes great pains to paint a =E2=80=98no-win=
=E2=80=99=C2=A0scenario for crypto assets,=E2=80=9D and:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The proposing release also explicitly states t=
hat =E2=80=93 because crypto assets trade on platforms that are not qualifi=
ed custodians =E2=80=93 an adviser that trades crypto assets on a platform =
would violate the proposed rule.=C2=A0Hence, the preamble in the proposing =
release indicates that it is unlikely that crypto assets can be maintained =
at qualified custodians or traded on crypto trading platforms in compliance=
 with the proposed rule. How could an adviser seeking to comply with this r=
ule possibly invest client funds in crypto assets after reading this releas=
e?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This approach to custody appears to mask a pol=
icy decision to block access to crypto as an asset class.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Another point is, you know, the SEC is not wro=
ng. Crypto exchanges=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>have a long history of losing cu=
stomer assets, and of landing in bankruptcy with customers who are very con=
fused specifically about=C2=A0<em>custody=C2=A0</em>questions. Crypto excha=
nges mostly create the=C2=A0<em>impression=C2=A0</em>that they segregate cu=
stomer assets, and then mostly end up with customers who are unsecured cred=
itors in bankruptcy. Even Coinbase, which does seem to <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMDkvYmFua21hbi1mcmllZC1zLWZ0e=
C1oYWQtYS1kZWF0aC1zcGlyYWwtYmVmb3JlLWJpbmFuY2UtZGVhbD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjE2MjNf=
TU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGV=
ybT0yMzAyMTYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0e7d8=
cd9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">  keep its customers=E2=80=99 crypto segregated</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuY29pbmRlc2suY29tL21hcmtldHMvMjAyMi8wNS8xMS9jb2luYmFzZS1oYXMtbm8tcmlz=
ay1vZi1iYW5rcnVwdGN5LW5ldy0xMC1xLWRpc2Nsb3N1cmUtbGFuZ2F1Z2UtaXMtc2VjLXJlcXV=
pcmVtZW50LWNlby1hcm1zdHJvbmctc2F5cy8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB30a0e6fe" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> can=E2=80=99t definitively=C2=A0promise</a> them that they won=E2=80=
=99t be unsecured creditors in bankruptcy: The legal regimes for crypto cus=
tody are just less settled than the regimes for securities custody.=C2=A0</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One more point I=E2=80=99d like to make is abo=
ut the SEC=E2=80=99s creativity. The SEC does not =E2=80=9Cregulate crypto.=
=E2=80=9D In US law, at least some cryptocurrencies =E2=80=94=C2=A0the big =
ones, like Bitcoin and Ether=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0are classified as commodit=
ies not subject to SEC jurisdiction. But the SEC has launched a pretty comp=
rehensive offensive to take over crypto regulation:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The SEC <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNv=
bS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMDgvZ2FyeS1nZW5zbGVyLXdhbnRzLXRvLXJlZ3V=
sYXRlLWNyeXB0bz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjE2MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJn=
V0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAyMTYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c=
3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB46621259" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  argues</a> that when a=
 crypto project issues tokens to fund its development, those tokens are alm=
ost always securities: Other than a few grandfathered tokens like Bitcoin a=
nd Ether, most tokens are going to be securities subject to SEC jurisdictio=
n.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The SEC argues that interest-be=
aring crypto accounts =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMTcvc2VjLWNvbWVzLWZvci1nZW1pbmktdG9vLWxhdGU_Y21=
waWQ9QkJEMDIxNjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3=
NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMjE2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB3be053e2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">lending</a> and <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMTMvdGhlLXNlYy1jcmFja3MtZG93bi1vbi1jc=
nlwdG8_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIxNjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291=
cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMjE2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB618e8d19" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  staking</a> products =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0are always securities; if a crypto exchange holds your Bitcoin for yo=
u and pays you interest, that=E2=80=99s a security subject to SEC jurisdict=
ion.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The SEC here is using its aut=
hority to regulate investment advisers to indirectly regulate crypto: Inves=
tment funds are subject to SEC regulation, so the SEC will tell them what t=
o do with their crypto, even if that crypto is not a security.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A general theme of financial regulation is tha=
t regulators write rules, and then creative financial-industry lawyers find=
 ways around them. The industry lawyers tend to have advantages over the re=
gulators: They are better paid, for one thing, but also the regulators have=
 to write general public rules that account for all cases and then the indu=
stry lawyers get to poke holes in them at their leisure. I once <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMTMvY3J5cHRvLXdhbnRz=
LXNvbWUtc2VjLXJ1bGVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMTYyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1=
haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIxNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW=
9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB29afa0c7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  wrote specificall=
y about crypto</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are the SEC, and crypto peo=
ple say =E2=80=9Cplease write clear transparent rules so we know what is an=
d isn=E2=80=99t allowed,=E2=80=9D you might hear that as =E2=80=9Cplease wr=
ite clear transparent rules so that we can game them.=E2=80=9D This would b=
e a reasonable lesson for the SEC to take from (1) the history of crypto=E2=
=80=99s =E2=80=9Ccode is law=E2=80=9D philosophy ending in hacks, (2) the h=
istory of crypto firms ignoring the US securities laws, and for that matter=
 (3) the history of traditional finance firms trying to game the SEC=E2=80=
=99s rules. Crypto is a wholly new area for US securities regulation, and i=
f you try to write all the rules from scratch in one go you will get things=
 wrong. And then people will ruthlessly exploit whatever you get wrong.</p>=
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And that is the stereotype: The industry is ru=
thless and creative about exploiting the rules, and the regulators are cons=
tantly playing catch-up.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I just want to say that in crypto right now th=
e SEC is being ruthless and creative about exploiting legal provisions to e=
xpand=C2=A0its powers, and the industry seems to be playing catch-up. Just =
an unusual situation!</p>
