<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have talked before about the problems of me=
me-stock corporate governance, and particularly=C2=A0the problem of meme-st=
ock shareholder voting. The problem is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you=E2=80=99re a weird public comp=
any with a very retail investor base, you will have a hard time getting you=
r shareholders to <em>vote=C2=A0</em>on anything, since retail shareholders=
 stereotypically do not vote.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If y=
ou=E2=80=99re a weird public company with a very retail investor base, you =
will probably end up=C2=A0<em>needing=C2=A0</em>your shareholders to vote f=
or something or other, because you=E2=80=99re weird.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Digital World Acquisition Corp. wanted to g=
et shareholder approval to extend the time on its deal to buy Donald Trump=
=E2=80=99s social media company, but <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
aW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMDYvdHJ1bXAtc3BhYy1kb2Vzbi10LWhhdmUtdGhlLXZvdGV=
zP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMTYyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT=
1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIxNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBb6568025" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  it couldn=E2=80=99t get it</a>, beca=
use the retail shareholders who were extremely enthusiastic about buying it=
s stock, and about the deal, were not enthusiastic enough to vote. Or AMC E=
ntertainment Holdings Inc. has a lot of enthusiastic retail shareholders, a=
nd it got very good at=C2=A0<em>selling them stock</em>, but it eventually =
ran out of authorized shares to sell, and it needed holders of a majority o=
f its outstanding shares to vote to authorize more, and it couldn=E2=80=99t=
 get enough votes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDItMDEvYW1jLWhhcy1zb21lLWNsZXZlci1hcGVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA=
yMTYyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJn=
V0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIxNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBab1e277a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">  (probably) solved this problem</a> with some clever =
engineering. It created a new class of preferred stock, gave each preferred=
 share 100 votes, and distributed 1/100th of a preferred share for each com=
mon share, basically a stock split where if you had one common share with o=
ne vote now you had one common share and 1/100th of a preferred share with =
a total of two votes. (The 1/100th of a preferred share is called an APE, a=
n AMC Preferred Equity Unit.) It=E2=80=99s not obvious that this would chan=
ge much =E2=80=94=C2=A0you still have to get a majority of the combined APE=
 and common holders to vote to authorize more shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0but AMC=
 added a clever twist. It issued the preferred shares to a depositary, Comp=
utershare Trust Co., and had Computershare issue the APE units to AMC=E2=80=
=99s shareholders. So now 100% of the preferred shares are owned, not by a =
bunch of retail shareholders, but by Computershare. The retail APE holders =
still get to vote, and Computershare still has to vote=C2=A0<em>its=C2=A0</=
em>shares however the APE holders vote, but Computershare has to vote=C2=A0=
<em>all=C2=A0</em>of the shares: If 20% of the APE holders vote yes, 5% vot=
e no, and 75% don=E2=80=99t vote at all, then Computershare will vote 80% o=
f the preferred shares for yes and 20% for no. AMC still needs to=C2=A0<em>=
win the vote</em>, but it has solved the problem of=C2=A0<em>retail shareho=
lders not voting at all</em>.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-=
3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impor=
tant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Soligenix Inc. is a micro-cap biotech company =
listed on the Nasdaq. Nasdaq will delist companies whose stocks trade below=
 $1 per share for an extended period. Soligenix=E2=80=99s stock traded belo=
w $1 for a long time, and Nasdaq <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdh=
ci9kYXRhLzgxMjc5Ni8wMDAxNTU4MzcwMjMwMDAwOTAvdG1iLTIwMjMwMjA4eGRlZjE0YS5odG0=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB983f0df4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">threatened=C2=A0it with delisti=
ng</a> starting in December 2021. By December 2022 it was still below $1 an=
d <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30575723.282980/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvODEyNzk2LzA=
wMDE1NTgzNzAyMjAxODk2OC90bWItMjAyMjEyMjB4OGsuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
81f8a705" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;"> in real danger of delisting</a>. The normal solution her=
e is a reverse stock split: If your stock trades at $0.70, and you do a 1-f=
or-10 reverse stock split, then every 10 shares (each worth $0.70) become o=
ne share, which should be worth $7.00. But you need shareholder approval fo=
r the split, and Soligenix was worried about its ability to get a majority =
of its retail, penny-stock shareholders to vote for anything.<a class=3D"fo=
otnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !import=
ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Soligenix came up with an APE-like solution=
. Like AMC, it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/305=
75723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzgxMjc5Ni=
8wMDAxNTU4MzcwMjIwMTg5ODcvdG1iLTIwMjIxMjIxeGV4OTlkMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB16bee007" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> issued new =E2=80=9Cblank-check preferred stock=
=E2=80=9D</a>; each share of its new Series D preferred stock came with=C2=
=A0<em>one million=C2=A0</em>votes.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foo=
tnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none =
!important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block=
;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And it distributed the preferred shares to its common shareholder=
s, giving them each 1/1,000th of a preferred share (with 1,000 votes) for e=
ach common share that they own. So effectively all of the voting power of t=
he company is in the Series D preferred, but the voting rights don=E2=80=99=
t really change, because every existing common shareholder owns the same pr=
oportional amount of Series D preferred.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the Series D preferred stock is a temporar=
y blip: Soligenix issued it in December, and it all disappeared last week.<=
a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transp=
arent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0It never traded, had no cash value, was issued to shareholders fo=
r $0 and then redeemed by the company for $0.<a class=3D"footnote-index" hr=
ef=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: in=
line-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a> For a couple of months Soligenix had some extra shares with billions o=
f votes, and now it doesn=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why? Well, here are the mechanics of how the S=
eries D disappeared:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">All shares of Series D Preferred S=
tock that are not present in person or by proxy at the meeting of stockhold=
ers held to vote on the reverse stock split as of immediately prior to the =
opening of the polls at such meeting will automatically be redeemed by the =
Company. Any outstanding shares of Series D Preferred Stock that have not b=
een so redeemed will be redeemed if such redemption is ordered by the Compa=
ny=E2=80=99s Board of Directors or automatically upon the approval by the C=
ompany=E2=80=99s stockholders of an amendment to the Company=E2=80=99s cert=
ificate of incorporation effecting the reverse stock split at such meeting.=
</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Get it? Soligenix <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30575723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9Bcm=
NoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzgxMjc5Ni8wMDAxNTU4MzcwMjMwMDAwOTAvdG1iLTIwMjMwMjA4e=
GRlZjE0YS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC983f0df4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> held a sharehold=
er meeting</a> last Wednesday, Feb. 8. If you voted at the shareholder meet=
ing =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is, if you filled out your proxy to vote your share=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0then your preferred stock got canceled immediately=C2=A0<e=
m>after=C2=A0</em>the vote. If you didn=E2=80=99t vote =E2=80=94=C2=A0if yo=
u forgot or were unreachable or whatever =E2=80=94=C2=A0then your preferred=
 stock got canceled immediately=C2=A0<em>before=C2=A0</em>the vote. At the =
moment of the vote, the preferred stock represented roughly 99.9% of the vo=
ting power of the company, and only the preferred shares that=C2=A0<em>actu=
ally voted=C2=A0</em>were outstanding. They voted overwhelmingly for the re=
verse split, and it passed.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a> Soligenix <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/305=
75723.282980/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzgxMjc5Ni=
8wMDAxNTU4MzcwMjMwMDEwNTYvdG1iLTIwMjMwMjA4eGV4OTlkMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB3c2ffb5e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> did a 1-for-15 reverse stock split</a>, and the =
Series D disappeared back into the lawyer=E2=80=99s imagination from whence=
 it came.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is this legal? I mean, the answer is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">nothing here is ever legal advice;</li=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">it is=C2=A0<em>funny</em>, anyway, an=
d isn=E2=80=99t that the=C2=A0<em>real=C2=A0</em>purpose of securities lawy=
ering; and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">who would=C2=A0<em>obje=
ct</em>?</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The large majority of the shareholders who bot=
hered to vote wanted this result; Soligenix just found a way to give it to =
them.=C2=A0</p>
