solid; background-color: #ccc;">The beguiling behaviour of narcissistic CEO=
s: Evidence from repurchase announcements</a>,=E2=80=9D by Evans Ofosu Boam=
ah and Shantanu Banerjee of Lancaster University, which on=C2=A0one level f=
inds that companies with narcissistic chief executive officers are more lik=
ely to announce large share buybacks, but less likely to actually complete =
those buybacks:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Using signature characteristics as=
 a measure of narcissism, we find that US firms with narcissist CEOs are mo=
re likely to make repurchase announcements and announce higher repurchase d=
ollar amounts. However, these firms are less likely to follow through. They=
 repurchase less and a small dollar amount when they make an actual repurch=
ase in the announcement year. The higher rate and amount of repurchase anno=
uncements are more pronounced in poorly-governed firms with narcissistic CE=
Os. These results are robust to various specifications including a differen=
ce-in-difference specification using CEOs=E2=80=99 exogenous turnover, cont=
rolling for other CEO traits and using an alternative measure of narcissism=
 based on pronoun usage in CEO communications. Collectively, the results pr=
esented in this study demonstrate that narcissist CEOs play a critical role=
 in the intensity of share repurchase announcements and their executions, p=
articularly for firms with weaker governance structure.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But at another level it demonstrates that fina=
ncial academics can spend their time analyzing CEO signatures =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0like, literally, how they sign their names =E2=80=94 and then trying to =
correlate those signatures to financial outcomes:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Psychology literature argues that =
handwriting styles reflect personality (Chaudhari and Thakkar, 2019). In li=
ne with this, we measure CEO narcissism using the area per character signat=
ure size narcissism measure. Using an unobtrusive measure such as signature=
 size reduces the=C2=A0 reactivity, researcher expectation and demand chara=
cteristics that can weaken the measure=E2=80=99s validity (Chatterjee and H=
ambrick, 2007). We draw a rectangle that touches the CEO signature=E2=80=99=
s edges to measure the area per character signature size. We measure the ar=
ea by multiplying the length and width of the rectangle. We measure CEO nar=
cissism by dividing the area by the number of characters in the CEO=E2=80=
=99s signed name. According to our prediction, the greater a CEO=E2=80=99s =
narcissism score, as measured by the signature size, the more likely the an=
nouncement of repurchases and target a larger dollar amount.</p></blockquot=
e>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I feel like that=E2=80=99s the sort of thing y=
ou can do in academia. If you work at a hedge fund and you go to your boss =
and say =E2=80=9CI am going to predict how much stock our portfolio compani=
es will buy back by taking a tape measure to the CEO=E2=80=99s signature in=
 the proxy statement,=E2=80=9D what would your boss say? I actually don=E2=
=80=99t know? I feel like I am going to get some emails that are like =E2=
=80=9CI work at a hedge fund and we use handwriting analysis all the time t=
o predict short-term stock price moves.=E2=80=9D Really finance is the stud=
y of human behavior and I guess signing your name really big is a human beh=
avior like anything else, apparently one that correlates with stock buyback=
 announcements.</p>
